stisch-rhetorischen Analyse mit rezeptions- und produktionsästhetischen Fragestellungen neue Kontexte dafür finden, was Mirjam im Text repräsentiert. Sie kann nicht länger als "Prophetin" aus der Frühzeit Israels betrachtet werden, sondern steht vielmehr für eine bestimmte theopolitische Position in persischer Zeit.  aThis study examines the rhetoric of the Old Testament Miriam references and their socio-historical contexts, and processes the history of research into Miriam from a feminist perspective. Previous research into Miriam was largely determined by prior decisions on literary history, and was thus only able to make rudimentary statements about Miriam. In contrast, a feminist rhetorical analysis inquiring into the aesthetics of reception and production reveals new contexts for what Miriam represents in the text. She can no longer be regarded as a 'prophetess' from the early history of Israel, but instead represents a particular theo-political position in Persian times.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aTheology and Religious StudiesxOld Testament and Ancient Near EastxHistory of Reception. 0aTheology and Religious StudiesxOld Testament and Ancient Near EastxPentateuch and Historical BooksxPentateuch. 4aAltes Testament. 4aFeministische Exegese. 4aMirjam, Prophetin. 4aRhetorik. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Theology and Religious Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110638165oZDB-23-GTR0 cprintz978311017384040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311089236940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110892369423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110892369/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aP